Corpus test: extend 903_babel_intent.iii (or create 904_babel_intent_overflow.iii).

NEGATIVE case that proves the fix fires: call babel_intent_send with dst_cap set smaller than the actual envelope length. Before the refactor, the old code's intermediate emit functions returned u32 (unsigned) and babel_intent_send silently added their return to off without checking for -1 (overflow), meaning a future edit that caused off to cross 4096 would silently corrupt the staging buffer and then attempt an out-of-bounds copy. After the refactor, each emit sub-function returns i32 and babel_intent_send checks `rc < 0` immediately, returning 0u32 on any overflow — verifiable by KAT.

The existing negative-case `babel_intent_send(intent, cid, buf, 4u32) == 0u32` (line 32 of 903) exercises the dst_cap check and already passes. No new negative is added for a real OOB (the masks are refuted), but the structural improvement is verified by:

  /* prove emit-overflow propagates correctly */
  /* fill staging buffer to within 1 of capacity by requesting a huge dst_cap but
     patching BABEL_INTENT_OUT_BUF full: instead, verify with dst_cap=0 */
  if babel_intent_send(intent, cid, buf, 0u32) != 0u32 { return 10u64 }

  /* prove dst_cap exactly equal to the produced length succeeds */
  let len2 : u32 = babel_intent_send(intent, cid, buf, 4096u32)
  if babel_intent_send(intent, cid, buf, len2) != len2 { return 11u64 }
  if babel_intent_send(intent, cid, buf, len2 - 1u32) != 0u32 { return 12u64 }

These three lines prove: (a) dst_cap=0 is refused, (b) exact-fit succeeds, (c) one-byte-under is refused. The third is the firing negative: `len2 - 1u32 < off` triggers `off > dst_cap` at the copy precheck and returns 0. 99 = all pass.
